# Lebanon Monitor — Project Context

## What This Project Is
A real-time intelligence dashboard for Lebanon that aggregates, classifies, and visualizes public data on an interactive map. Inspired by World Monitor (koala73/worldmonitor) but focused exclusively on Lebanon with a dual Lumière/Ombre (positive/negative) classification framework.

## Tech Stack
- **Runtime**: Node.js 20+ / TypeScript 5+
- **Framework**: Next.js 14+ (App Router)
- **Map**: Leaflet or Mapbox GL JS
- **Charts**: Recharts or Plotly.js
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS
- **Data fetching**: Server-side API routes + client SWR/React Query
- **Testing**: Vitest + Playwright (e2e)
- **Linting**: ESLint + Prettier
- **Deployment**: Vercel

## Architecture Principles
- All data flows through typed TypeScript interfaces
- Each data source is an independent module in `src/sources/`
- Every source module exports: `fetch()`, `normalize()`, `classify()`
- Normalized data conforms to `LebanonEvent` interface
- Classification outputs `lumiere | ombre | neutre` with confidence score
- No hardcoded API keys — use `.env.local` and `process.env`
- Prefer server-side data fetching via Next.js API routes to avoid CORS
- Cache aggressively with appropriate TTLs per source

## Code Style
- TypeScript strict mode, no `any` types
- Functional style, no classes unless wrapping external SDKs
- Named exports only (no default exports except pages/layouts)
- Error handling with early returns and custom error types
- All functions documented with JSDoc
- File naming: kebab-case for files, PascalCase for components
- French comments allowed in data classification logic, English everywhere else
- No console.log in production — use structured logger

## Git Conventions
- Conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `docs:`, `test:`
- Branch naming: `feat/source-gdelt`, `fix/api-timeout`
- Atomic commits — one logical change per commit

## What NOT To Do
- Never commit API keys or tokens
- Never use `fetch` without timeout and error handling
- Never ignore TypeScript errors with `@ts-ignore`
- Never leave dead code or unused imports
- Never create files without updating the barrel export (`index.ts`)
- Never mock API responses in production code
